    slug: 'ocean-freight-vs-air-freight-choosing-right',
    title: 'Ocean Freight vs Air Freight: How to Choose the Right Option',
    excerpt: 'A comprehensive comparison guide to help businesses decide between ocean and air freight based on cost, speed, cargo type, and environmental impact.',
    content: `<p>One of the most critical decisions in international logistics is choosing between ocean freight and air freight. Each mode has distinct advantages and trade-offs that can significantly impact your bottom line.</p>
    <h3>Cost Comparison</h3>
    <p>Ocean freight is significantly cheaper per kilogram than air freight, typically costing 12-16 times less. For large, heavy shipments that aren't time-sensitive, ocean freight is the clear winner. However, the cost advantage diminishes for smaller shipments where minimum container charges apply.</p>
    <h3>Speed and Transit Times</h3>
    <p>Air freight delivers goods in 1-3 days compared to 20-45 days for ocean freight. For perishable goods, high-value electronics, or urgent medical supplies, air freight is essential. WTL offers express air freight services with guaranteed delivery windows.</p>
    <h3>Cargo Suitability</h3>
    <p>Ocean freight accommodates virtually any cargo size, from a single pallet to entire industrial plants. Special container types (refrigerated, open-top, flat rack) handle diverse cargo needs. Air freight has stricter size and weight limitations but offers superior handling for fragile items.</p>
    <h3>Environmental Considerations</h3>
    <p>Ocean freight produces approximately 10-40 grams of CO2 per ton-kilometer, while air freight generates 500-600 grams. Companies with sustainability goals should factor environmental impact into their logistics decisions.</p>
    <h3>The WTL Recommendation</h3>
    <p>At WTL, we help clients find the optimal balance. Our multimodal solutions often combine both modes — using air freight for urgent components and ocean freight for bulk materials — to maximize efficiency and minimize costs.</p>`,
